In a small pot, bring 1 cup @water{1%cup} to a boil with a large pinch of @salt{pinch}. Once boiling, add the @Jasmine Rice{1/2%cup}, cover, and reduce to a low simmer for ~{15-20%minutes}, until tender. Keep covered off the heat until the rest of the meal is ready.

Prep the ingredients: halve, peel, and thinly slice the @Red Onion{1%unit}(halved, peeled, and thinly sliced). Dice the @Russet Potato{12%ounce}(diced into 1/2-inch cubes) into ½-inch cubes. Finely chop the @Cilantro{1/4%ounce}(finely chopped), reserving a few leaves for garnish. Mince the @Jalapeño{1%unit}(minced, ribs and seeds removed if preferred less heat). Add the @Curry Powder{1%tablespoon} and @Coriander{1%teaspoon}(to taste, start with 1 teaspoon and add incrementally).

> Be sure to wash your hands and surfaces after handling the jalapeño; the heat is transferable and can burn more than just your throat!

Heat @Olive Oil{2%teaspoon} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add the onion, coriander, jalapeño, and curry powder. Cook, tossing, for ~{3-4%minutes}, until softened. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}.

Add the potatoes to the #pan{} along with the @Coconut Milk{14%ounce} and enough water to cover the potatoes by 1 inch. Bring to a boil, then reduce to a simmer and cook for ~{12-15%minutes}, until the potatoes are fork tender.

Cut the @Catfish{12%ounce}(cut into 1-2 inch pieces) into 1-2 inch pieces. When the potatoes are tender, add the @Peas{4%ounce}, chopped cilantro, and catfish to the broth. Cook for ~{2-3%minutes}, until the fish is just opaque. Taste and season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}.

Fluff the rice with a #fork{}. Ladle the fish curry into #bowls{}, then top with a scoop of rice and the reserved cilantro. Enjoy!